Kenya on Saturday recorded 122 new Covid-19 cases from a sample size of 2,391 tested in the last 24 hours. The positivity rate is now at 5.1 per cent. The Health Ministry said in a statement 106 of the newly infected individuals are Kenyans while 16 are foreigners. It said 66 of them are females while 56 are males. The youngest is a four-year-old child while the oldest is 80 years old. Kenya's total confirmed positive cases are now 325,442 while cumulative tests conducted so far are 3,679,918. Health CS Mutahi Kagwe said 57 patients have recovered from the disease, all from the Home-Based and Isolation Care Program. "This pushes the total recoveries to 318,755 of whom 265,724 are from the Home-Based Care and Isolation program, while 53,031 are from various health facilities countrywide," he said in the statement. No patient succumbed to the disease meaning the cumulative fatalities remain at 5,651. There are six patients currently admitted in various health facilities while 1,030 are under the Home-Based Isolation and Care program. No patient is in the Intensive Care Unit (ICU), none is on supplemental oxygen and no patient is in the High Dependency Unit (HDU). So far, Kenya has administered 18,265,077 vaccines. The government is working towards vaccinating 27,246,033 people by December 2022.